It is 157.4 in May 2022. Mean is quite a bit lower so will likely drop or stay same. Large drop very unlikely. Why? Summer will call for more eating in western world. Ukraine, crops at risk be it that some are being stolen by Russia - at least that's likely.

From May to June 2021, the index dropped by four points. I think this reflects a seasonal pattern, where foods are more plentiful in the summer so the prices fall as we move into June. I don't know if that will be the case this year or to what extent the index for May 2022 at 157 points will fall, but I'm leaving some possibility for prices to land in the 140 to 150 range in June 2022.

With prices continue to be elevated due to the war in Ukraine and droughts in large portions of the world, it is almost certain the FAO index will stay above 150.

Cereals Price Index and Vegetable Oil Price Index impacts increasing global index value. Cereals index might increase while Ukrania war continues, even keep increasing after finished. In june value will be between 153-155.
Updating with May index: lower than my forecast (160,5), though still well above 150 (157,4).
Ukraine war causing shortages. Climate change impacts on production

Its June, and the figure for May is now available - as I understand it this is the last one we'll get before the one that resolves the question next month. The index is now at 157.4 - down from 158.5 when I read it a month ago, and 159.3 two months ago. Still well above 150.0 though, and I believe this is only a temporary dip (due to summer?) on the way to higher prices later this year.

May's value came out at 157 again. IT's leveled off a bit in the last three months and now is only a 5% drop or so to get below 150. That's a huge monthly move, but probabyl a small chance of it so giving a few percent to the 140-150 bucket:
Although the index has been slowly decreasing since the March peak of 159.7 (it was 157.4 for May), it is highly unlikely that it will retreat below 150 in just one month.
Adjusting for 100% higher than 150 since I don't think there's enough time to lower commodity prices until June, despite many signs of demand destruction.
with the index at 158 in may, highly unlikely it will decrease to under 150.

Continued blockage of ports in Ukraine and concerns over 2022 crop conditions in the United States of America will keep prices elevated, and I anticipate that the export restrictions placed by India will maybe undo some of the easing seen in April as concerns over supply continue. There has been no real change in the global environment between april and may, and more awareness that a food shortage is a probable outcome.
There are almost no factors that make it cheaper;
Adjusting the distribution since there’s not enough time to change current trend.

Continued upward pressure on food in latest CPI report (17th consecutive monthly increase): https://www.bls.gov/news.release/pdf/cpi.pdf

Its May, and the latest index figure is actually down slightly at 158.5 (from 159.3 when I read it a month ago). This is mostly caused by a large drop in the price of vegetable oils, though they are still substantially more expensive than at the beginning of the year. Cereals have also dropped a tiny bit, everything else is creeping up.
Latest reading for April is at 158, just a tick below March’s 159. The likelihood of falling below 150 in next two months looks slim to quite slim.
Indonesia edible oil export ban caused a 10% increase in palm oil prices.

Concerns over wheat exports from Russia and Ukraine should support cereal prices, while higher fertilizer prices could negatively impact the level of technology used on most crops and should affect the world's SnD, especially for corn and soybeans. Protective measures from some governments should also help sustain a higher reference, sensitive for oils. Meat prices should continue to go up due to avian flu in the US and higher pork prices in the EU, US, and China. For dairy, with higher grain prices, I'd expect an uptrend in the following months.
Inflationary pressures will continue for the rest of the year.

"The FAO Food Price Index* (FFPI) averaged 159.3 points in March 2022, up 17.9 points (12.6 percent) from February, making a giant leap to a new highest level since its inception in 1990. The latest increase reflects new all-time highs for vegetable oils, cereals and meat sub-indices, while those of sugar and dairy products also rose significantly" April 8, 2022 FAO report
tought times ahead
Probably the index will climb down from the March peak in April; lingering between 154 - 157 for the next couple of months is a real possibility
Grain and other futures are still really high.

March 22 is 159.3, so we are already past the 150 threshold for bin 5. There seems very little prospect in any decrease in food prices this year, which would be needed to do anything but bin 5 on this question. Although the rate of increase probably will slow.

Data for March 2022 saw a significant increase in the FPI over February by 12.6% and 33.6% March (yr/yr). Surges in prices for Cereals, Vegetable oils and Fertilizers were realized. Russia and Ukraine account for 40% of global wheat exports and 80% of global sunflower exports. Given the conflict between the two nation states, supply disruptions, tight supply, and restricted export conditions (for varying reasons) persist. Restricted and taxed exports contribute to a worsening food security situation and a higher FPI. Given the empirical data and functional change in material conditions, we can expect a further change in FPI which will exceed the baseline in the IFP. Sanctions by the EU on imports from Russia over the last couple days have some but not a major impact on FPI and does not change the underlying assessment dramatically. A customs official on the Russian border has been cited : “According to available information, the restrictions do not yet apply to road freight transport delivering pharmaceutical, medical, food and agricultural products, including wheat, as well as the delivery of energy, non-ferrous metals and fertilizers.”

we are in unprecedented territory now; annual drops of 30 points or more are large outliers. even if the war ends today, it will take months and maybe years to rebuild capacity to grow, harvest, and ship food, so we are likely to see these numbers go up more than down.
New FAO print is 159.3, a new maximum (immediately after a prior maximum). Fastest MoM rise in the index EVER.

Repeating my forecast. The index is currently at 159.3 for March. I don't expect it to fall much in April, if at all; it could even increase. But grain and other prices could be slightly lower overall in April. I do think the index will fall eventually, and it has a fair amount of volatility, but it's not clear to me whether it will fall below 150 in the time scale of this forecast. I expect it to remain high (>120) for at least 1-2 years, in general. I'm just not sure yet just how high it might go, and how long it will stay so high.

March's data is out, the overall index is at 159.3 (up from 140.7 last time I reviewed it). This is now in the highest band, by no small margin, with three months left on the question. I believe most of the causes (war in Ukraine, sanctions on Russia, high fuel prices, impact of Covid-19, general inflation...) are still at full effect so I expect prices will grow even higher. There's a small hope that changes in usage (e.g. lower meat consumption, using alternative vegetable oils?) could help, or that some of the prices are being affected by temporary speculation which could ease.
March reading was 159.3, noticeably above the top threshold by 9.3% with 3 more readings before now and the deadline.

March index now reported at 159.3, up 17.9 points (!!!) m-o-m. Leaving a small probability that this is a transient, short-lived spike. However, there is no indication that any of the main drivers (including Ukraine conflict) will end soon.
The index reached 159 in march. Assuming the price shock from the Russian invasion will subside in the coming months, it will be around 140-155
Maybe it could come back down a little by then, but probably not. https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2022/apr/02/global-food-price-fears-as-ukraine-farmers-forced-to-reduce-crop-planting
I am adjusting my forecast. I think in June food prices will be up to 10 points higher than now. FPI was 140.7 in February 2022.

current index 141, increase some 2/month, so extrapolated this gives 149. But cereal production in India and other reasons looks higher than estimated and domestic utilization in India is reduced compared to forecast. Hence increase of 2/month is a high estimate (it would lead to 149 in June).

I think the index will be over 150 in a month or 2, given the war in Ukraine's effects on cereals and oils, on top of high fertilizer prices, ongoing pandemic problems, etc. The question is whether it might fall enough by June to be under 150. Probably not, as Putin is likely to press ahead for quite a while, and Ukrainian and Russian exports would be cut as a result.

New all time high printed for FAO food price index, up a scorching 5.3 points to 140.7. This number doesn't even incorporate the price shocks from Russian sanctions, the ban on Russian fertilizer exports, the ban on Russian natural gas to make fertilizer with, Ukraine banning their wheat exports 09MAR2022, Hungary banning their grain exports 05MAR2022, or the post-sanctions spike in cooking oil prices (because of sanctioned sunflower oil).

As of writing this forecast the latest FAO Food Price Index was 140.7 as per the February reading. This is a new all time high for the index, with prices being on a drastic rise since 2020. This most recent rise can mainly be attributed to supply shocks caused by the ongoing conflict in Ukraine(Cereal -- ie Wheat & Vegetable Oil -- ie sunflower oil), issue with the South American Soy harvest (Vegetable Oil -- ie Soy Oil), and decreased Palm Oil Exports from Indonesia (Vegetable Oil). Putting immense upward pressure on the price of Cereal and Vegetable Oil components of the Index.

February number rising to 140.7. Still anticipating FED action in March meeting. Based on how the rate setting decision goes and other inflation factors settling in through the military action in Ukraine.

I think I under-corrected on my last update. Putting more weight into the highest bucket. See, for example: https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-60653856 "Analysts have warned that war could impact the production of grains and even double global wheat prices."...

Impact of Ukraine war looks to be massive and outside of any historical precedent in terms of the amount of wheat coming offline. That, plus higher energy costs, is driving food prices up fast. I know a 10% jump in 5 months sounds extreme, but these are extreme times. Upping to 50/50

Instead of trying to create a global unified commodity forecasting model, I just simply looked at two broad macro scenarios and started from there.

135.7 for Jan 2022, up 1.5 points. 5 more months to go. I'll weight the last bin lower, as prices have been relatively flat for the past few months. I still anticipate price increases through June overall, for many reasons, including high fertilizer prices and the situation in Ukraine. Average 1 point/month increase => 140.7 2/month => 145.7 3+/month => 150.7 So if prices go up by an average of 1 to ~3/month, the forecast will end up in bin 4.
The FAO Food Price Index has been > 130 since 2021, therefore using 130 as my base.

New data point for January 2022—135.7—suggests that a continuing upward trend of the index is most likely. Linear fit of monthly values from July 2021 to Jan 2022 suggests average of ~1.8 point increase/mo to be expected if current trends continue. In other words, if the past 6-7 months’ trend continues, we’d be on track for a solid mid-bin #4 outcome. For benchmarking purposes, under this model, expect: Feb. 2022 ~ 137.5 Mar. 2022 ~ 139.3

I limited my time frame to December 2009 to December 2021 (the most recent Food Price Index value available). What I found is that June is typically the lowest value for the Food Price Index throughout the year. I calculate a 95% confidence interval between 93 and 132.
I think Russia is going to invade Ukraine, and with Ukraine being one of the bread-basket countries to the world, this won't help food prices stay lower. Just revising my forecast slightly higher.

I focused on the graphs available from https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/. It appears that in the June/July timeframe, the index was around 95. COVID changed that, but there does still appear to be a dip in the index in the early summer months, no matter what. I'm using that as my base rate consideration, though this doesn't adjust/account for inflation.

There has been a slow exponential increase month over month since July 2021 but only 0.5-1 points a month - assuming same continued growth - June would be high 130's, potentially getting into 140's - but it could also potentially decrease as the economy recovers/supply chain problems are resolved - spliting my other predictions between the categories on either side of the 130-140 range.
Base rate: FFPI data between 2019-2021 (December). The FFPI has not exceeded 140 points in the records kept since 2004.

Trend prices in recent years (exclusive of 2020 and 2021) tend to move (roughly) plus or minus 5 points, 2021 ended mid130s after large rises in 2021. With many supply chains issues and cash flow needs by producers upward and downward pressures and unusual frictions make this a tough call. Volatility will probably be high. Some of the increases in 2021 may be offset.
I understand the index is currently around 126. Guessing that it will rise further conforms to a consensus view on inflation.

The market factors driving food price seem to be roughly based on global GDP/inflaction based on the historic values in the table at the link. The previous peaks occurred in the late 1970s and early 2010s which at a macro level are within 3-4 years after major recession.

running the numbers (moving average on different time periods (3 - 6 - 12 months)) it is most likely to end between 140 and 150 though in the last 30 years this range not occur.
Assuming 12.5% annual volatility results in this distribution. This looks like a classic case where the volatility is completely underdiscounted by the crowd.

A sustained decline in the food price index would require either increased production or decreased demand in cereals (wheat, maize, rice), meat, dairy products (milk, cheese, yogurt), vegetable oils (palm, olive, corn), and sugar. Economists largely agree that inflation has so far done little to reduce consumer demand, and food is the most inelastic of commodities (i.e., unlikely that its price would drive down demand for all but the poorest consumers). The omicron variant and bad weather are further depressing supply chains and crop yields, according to USDA, so the production side looks slim at the moment. Given that the question's end date is only 5 months away, the index seems likely to stay above 130, with a moderate chance of going above 140.
Seems pretty unlikely that the index will decrease significantly (bins #1-2) while La Niña climate, energy/fertilizer production and logistics will continue to impact prices throughout our timeframe.

The FAO Food Price Index (FFPI) averaged 133.7 points in December 2021, down 1.2 points (0.9 percent) from November, but still up 25.1 points (23.1 percent) from December 2020. Except for dairy, the values of all sub-indices encompassed by the FFPI registered monthly declines, with international prices of vegetable oils and sugar falling significantly month-on-month. https://www.fao.org/worldfoodsituation/foodpricesindex/en/

I'm quite sure it will go up on the forecast period; the only question is how much. In case I'm wrong, I'm leaving a little weight on the 2 lowest bins. If it goes up as much in the next 6 months as it has in the previous 6, it will end up in the last bin, just barely. I'm leaving some substantial weight on bin 3 in case the increase slows a lot. As I wrote in a previous forecast, I do think prices will eventually fall again, but I don't see them falling in the forecast period because a variety of pandemic dislocations are still in play, and on top of that, many fertilizer prices are at an all-time high. I can't imagine yields that rely on fertilizer will be quite as high as previously, even if the weather cooperates.
forecast is consistent with FPI over past year

Reviewed the FFPI by month going back to 1990. The month-to-month average was 0.18 with stdev of 2.27. The absolute month-to-month change averaged 1.55 points with a stdev of 1.66. Dec 21 was at 133.7. However, it has been much more volatile in the past year, with an average change of 2.09 (stdev 2.6).

Food production increase reflects utilisation increase, mitigating potential excess supply’s adverse price effects. Fixing supply chain disruptions could put downward price pressure.
Food prices will stabilize as the world starts to see Covid decline in the spring. It has already started

I'm new to this subject, but it seems like the causes of recently high food prices are not likely to go away suddenly, and even if they did it would take time for the effects to work their way through the seasons and supply chains. On the other hand if things continue as they are I imagine prices will continue to push upwards.

"The FFPI averaged 133.7 points in December 2021, down 1.2 points (0.9%) from November, but still up 25.1 points (23.1%) from December 2020. Except for dairy, the values of all sub-indices encompassed by the FFPI registered monthly declines, with international prices of vegetable oils and sugar falling significantly month-on-month. For 2021 as whole, the FFPI averaged 125.7 points, as much as 27.6 points (28.1%) above the previous year with all sub-indices averaging sharply higher than in the previous year." So far, with all the issues the world inherited from the past 2 years, and the still lingering uncertainty regarding virus spread (still half of the world's population is unvaccinated, and over a billion are vaccinated with Sinovac, coronovac, which do not protect against omicron -- more disruption, shortages and delays are to be expected. Cost of production, transportation not likely to go down in the next 6 months.
Inflation.
Three of the sub indexes have dropped slightly..I think the peak has been reached.

This year, fertilizer is going to be a big issue. Fertilizer prices started rising last year, after it was relevant for the last crop. Farmers aren't going to use as much fertilizer this year because the prices are just too high. They're finding alternative sources, but it's hard to replace standard commercial fertilizer. With fertilizer prices continuing to rise, it seems likely to me that the food price index will likely continue to climb. The climb in fertilizer prices is starting to slow, but many key ingredients are at all-time highs. In addition, so many of the pandemic issues that drove up the food price index over the past 2 years are still unresolved. And now Omicron is sweeping the world, even as Delta isn't overwith, either. There are 6 months in this forecast. It would not be impossible for the index to end up in any bin. Last year, the index went up 16.7 points from Dec 2020 to June 2021. If it did the same this year, it would end up at 150.4, right on the edge between bins 4 and 5, so I'll focus my forecast there. As there is a lot of uncertainty, I will cast a wide net beneath bin 4, too.
